# Memory Protocol

> An AI that forgets everything between sessions is an AI that makes the same mistakes forever. This protocol defines exactly what gets written, where, and when — so the system compounds knowledge instead of resetting it.

---

## The Memory Layer

```
tasks/
  todo.md          ← active task tracking (Zeus writes and updates)
  lessons.md       ← self-improvement log (Zeus writes after every correction)
  decisions.md     ← architectural and tool decisions (Zeus writes on every key decision)
```

These three files are the system's long-term memory. They are read at session start and written throughout the session.

---

## Session Start Protocol

Zeus executes this silently at the start of every session before taking any action:

```
1. READ tasks/lessons.md
   → Load all patterns and prevention rules into active context
   → Identify any lessons directly relevant to the current task type

2. READ tasks/decisions.md
   → Load architectural decisions that constrain current work
   → Check for decisions that may affect the current task

3. READ tasks/todo.md
   → Are there incomplete items from the previous session?
   → If yes: surface them to the user before starting anything new
```

> Skipping session start reads is how systems repeat mistakes. Zeus never skips.

---

## `tasks/todo.md` — Active Task Tracking

**Format:**

```markdown
# Active Tasks

## [Task Title] — [date started]
**Status:** In Progress / Blocked / Complete
**Assigned agents:** [list]

### Plan
- [ ] Step 1
- [x] Step 2 (complete)
- [ ] Step 3

### Blockers
- [any current blockers]

### Review
[Zeus writes this section when task closes — summary of what was done and outcome]
```

**Zeus writes to this file:**
- At task start: creates entry with plan steps as checkable items
- During task: marks steps complete as agents finish them
- On blocker: adds blocker entry
- At task close: adds Review section and marks status Complete

---

## `tasks/lessons.md` — Self-Improvement Log

**Purpose:** Every mistake, correction, or unexpected outcome becomes a rule that prevents recurrence.

**Format:**

```markdown
## [date] — [short pattern title]

**What happened:**
[Describe the mistake or unexpected outcome in one paragraph]

**Root cause:**
[Why it happened — be specific]

**Prevention rule:**
[The rule Zeus and agents must follow to prevent this]

**Applies to:**
[Which agents / task types this rule affects]
```

**Zeus writes to this file:**
- After any user correction
- After any agent rework cycle
- After any quality gate failure
- After any on-the-fly tool creation (lesson: what gap existed and why)

> Lessons are reviewed at session start. They are ruthlessly iterated — if a lesson's prevention rule doesn't stop the mistake, the rule is rewritten until it does.

---

## `tasks/decisions.md` — Architectural Decision Record

**Purpose:** Every significant decision — architectural, tooling, agent design — is logged with its rationale. Future sessions don't re-debate settled questions.

**Format:**

```markdown
## [date] — [decision title]

**Decision:**
[What was decided]

**Context:**
[What situation prompted this decision]

**Alternatives considered:**
- [Option A] — rejected because [reason]
- [Option B] — rejected because [reason]

**Rationale:**
[Why this decision was made]

**Consequences:**
[What this decision constrains or enables going forward]

**Status:** Active / Superseded by [link]
```

**Zeus writes to this file:**
- When a new tool is created (on-the-fly protocol)
- When an architectural pattern is chosen
- When an agent boundary is changed
- When a new agent is added to the roster
- When a quality gate threshold is adjusted

---

## Memory Hygiene Rules

| Rule | Why |
|---|---|
| Never delete lessons — only mark superseded | Deletion loses the history of why a rule existed |
| Never edit decisions without adding a superseding entry | Edits hide the reasoning trail |
| Todo items marked complete stay in the file for 1 session, then archived | Keeps todo.md actionable without losing history |
| Lessons are written in plain language — no jargon | They must be understood at session start in seconds, not decoded |
| Every lesson must have a prevention rule — observation alone is not a lesson | "X happened" is a log entry. "When X happens, do Y instead" is a lesson |

---

## What Memory Is Not

- Memory is not a chat log — it is structured, actionable knowledge
- Memory is not a status report — it is a prevention and decision system
- Memory is not optional — a session that doesn't write to memory has not fully completed its task
